<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How do I calculate how much wallpaper I need?", answer: "Measure the room perimeter by adding the length of all walls. Divide the perimeter by the width of one wallpaper strip (typically 20.5 inches for American rolls) to get the total number of strips. Then determine how many strips you can cut from one roll based on wall height and pattern repeat. Divide total strips by strips per roll and round up." },
  { question: "What is a standard wallpaper roll size?", answer: "An American single roll is approximately 20.5 inches wide and 33 feet long, covering about 56 square feet before trimming. A European roll is typically 21 inches wide and 33 feet long. Double rolls are twice the length at 66 feet. Always check the specific roll dimensions printed on the packaging, as sizes vary by manufacturer." },
  { question: "How does pattern repeat affect wallpaper quantity?", answer: "Pattern repeat is the vertical distance between identical points in the pattern. When hanging wallpaper, each strip must be aligned with the adjacent strip, which means you may need to cut extra paper to match the pattern. A large pattern repeat of 24 inches or more can increase waste by 20-30%. This calculator accounts for pattern repeat when estimating the number of strips per roll." },
  { question: "Should I subtract doors and windows from wallpaper calculations?", answer: "Yes. Each standard door saves approximately one wallpaper strip and each window saves about one strip. The calculator subtracts these openings from the total strip count. However, do not subtract half-strips for small windows or narrow openings, as you may still need a full-width strip for that section of wall." },
  { question: "How many extra rolls of wallpaper should I buy?", answer: "Buy at least one extra roll beyond the calculated amount for pattern matching waste, cutting errors, and future repairs. If the wallpaper has a large pattern repeat or the walls have many obstacles, buy two extra rolls. Always purchase all rolls from the same dye lot to ensure consistent color, as different print runs can vary slightly." }
]) %>

